In Java, data types are split into primitive types and reference types. int, double, and boolean are primitive types. String, Scanner, arrays, and custom classes are reference types.
A reference type is a data type that refers to an object in memory, rather than containing the object's data directly.
Consider Point as an example of a reference type.
Point = reference type / class
p = variable name
new Point(10, 20) = Point object created in memory
That object lives at a memory address.
p does not hold the full object directly ‚Äî it holds a reference to that memory location.
So p is like a label that knows where the Point object is.

Memory stack
Stack memory in Java is used for static memory allocation and the execution. of a thread. LIFO

Frame
A stack frame contains all the data for one function call.
The stack frame only exists during the execution time of a function including any references.

Heap
Space is used to store objects and JRE classes at runtime
New objects are always created in the heap space
References to these objects are stored in STACK MEMORY



int age = 21 - The value and the primitive are stored in the STACK

For reference types; values and object's memory address are stored in a frame on the stack. The object being referenced from the stack live on the HEAP

Strings are a bit different, they refer to the value within the string pool.
